{"id":2,"question":"What is in control of you?","rag_answer":"Based on the documents, there are two perspectives offered on what is in control of you:\n\n1. Life force energy.\n\n2. But more concretely, what is in control of you is your past, your trauma. How you reacted as a child in danger to love programmed your autonomic nervous system to either run away when you get triggered, or confront, or to embrace.\n\nThis is further elaborated upon: the patterns are so inbuilt in us that as soon as something triggers you that walks in the door, your heart rate already increases, stimulating more production of adrenaline and cortisol, that just makes you not want to be there.","label":"The answer pointed to is \"life force energy\". This is wrong since it was a question coming from someone else other than the speaker. Clear distinctions between speakers is required.\t\nThe transcript needs mixed voice recognition.\nAudio or transcript must undergo speaker diarization. \nChunks should be aligned with speaker turns.\n(Retrieval and generation handles metadata)"}
{"id":3,"question":"Please explain how the hypothalamus acts as the CEO","rag_answer":"Based on the documents, here is an explanation of how the hypothalamus acts as the CEO of the body:\n\nWhile many people mistakenly believe the pituitary gland is the \"president\" or big boss, it is actually more like the vice president. The true CEO is the hypothalamus.\n\nThe hypothalamus is part of the autonomic nervous system, the limbic system (which handles emotion and memory regulation), the endocrine system, and the circadian rhythms. There is no other brain part that regulates all of these functions as much as the hypothalamus.\n\nThe hypothalamus guides the pituitary, forming a deep partnership between the two. While the pituitary governs all the chakras, the hypothalamus governs the pituitary itself.\n\nThe hypothalamus oversees an extraordinarily wide range of functions, including sleep-wake cycles, dreaming patterns, breathing patterns, heart rate, thermoregulation, reproduction, sexual appetite, the ability to make babies, attention span, and memory. All of these are protected and held by the hypothalamus.\n\nSo if you can hold space for the hypothalamus, you can hold space for all.\n\nFinally, what makes this particularly relevant to innerdance is that the part of the brain that is the most sensitive to music is the hypothalamus — which helps explain why this work is capable of healing all kinds of things.","label":"Validate information pulled from scientific papers as much as possible"}
