{"id":70,"question":"Is innerdance the same as CAP?","rag_answer":"Based on the documents, the relationship between innerdance and CAP (Kundalini Activation Process) is complex. They share common roots but have significant differences.\n\nThe founder of CAP was an innerdance facilitator for one year, and then he decided he was going to gain a lot more by changing the brand, shifting the story, and working with the simple word \"Kundalini.\"\n\nThis means there is no separation between the Kundalini Activation Process and innerdance — it just depends on what part of the history you are interested in.\n\nHowever, there are notable distinctions in how the two practices evolved:\n\n- CAP was influenced by other teachers like Ratu Bagus and Adida, who believed in transmission. Cap took innerdance, which was coming from \"the mother,\" and reframed its source as coming from Adida.\n\n- A lot of the movements in CAP actually try to mimic a particular narrative in the body, creating a very strict image where the energy is coming from one person into another.\n\n- When you look at the old innerdance videos, there was diversity — the way people were moving their bodies had no format, there was no mold, there was just eclecticism.\n\n- The founder of CAP did learn the circadian rhythms or the 12-stage model in innerdance, but he just didn't teach it to the people he was training.\n\nSo while CAP originated from innerdance, it diverged significantly in its philosophy, structure, and movement approach.","label":"not CAP"}
{"id":71,"question":"What does CAP stand for in these teachings?","rag_answer":"Based on the documents provided, CAP is referenced as the **\"Kundalini Activation Process.\"** The founder of CAP was an inner dance facilitator for one year, and then he decided to gain more by changing the brand, shifting the story, and working with the simple word \"Kundalini.\"\n\nThe full name is spelled out more explicitly here: Right before the pandemic, CAP had already started, and the demand for the word was speeding up. It was described as an \"activation process\" — specifically by \"Venn\" (or \"Venom\").\n\nSo **CAP = Kundalini Activation Process**.","label":"CAP as a mis-transcription of KAP."}
{"id":72,"question":"When it is said that we are controlled by life force energy, is that the teacher's view?","rag_answer":"Based on the documents, the answer is nuanced. The term \"life force energy\" is mentioned, but the teacher actually moves past it to offer a more concrete explanation.\n\nWhen exploring what controls the autonomic nervous system — \"something's controlling you\" — the initial answer given is \"life force energy.\"\n\nHowever, the teacher then deliberately steers away from this framing:\n\n\"Let's be more concrete so that you're not gonna end up looping in your own room, your teaching spaces. What is in control of you is your past, your trauma. How you reacted as a child in danger to love programmed your autonomic nervous system to either run away when you get triggered, or confront, or to embrace.\"\n\nSo while \"life force energy\" is offered as one answer, the teacher's own preferred view appears to be more grounded and practical — that what actually controls us is our **past and trauma**, which have programmed our autonomic nervous system's responses. The teacher seems to consciously redirect away from more abstract spiritual language toward this more concrete understanding, specifically to help facilitators avoid getting lost in vague concepts when teaching.","label":"\"Life force energy\" that line came from a student; must not attribute it to the teacher."}
{"id":73,"question":"In the exchange about being individuals versus connected to everything, who said what?","rag_answer":"Based on the documents provided, the texts don't clearly attribute specific statements to named individual speakers in a dialogue format — they read more like a single speaker's monologue or teaching, with occasional illustrative phrases that represent different perspectives or \"voices.\"\n\nHowever, I can point out some of the key ideas expressed:\n\nThe speaker suggests that \"you're actually speaking each other\" and that \"the only reason why you're speaking it is because the person is speaking to herself through you.\"\n\nThe speaker poses the question: \"What if every conversation is a conversation with the One? What if the next person that you're speaking to carries over the conversation that was happening yesterday? That everyone is just one being conversing with each other through us?\"\n\nThe speaker shares their own paradigm: \"I have a really strange paradigm where I really believe that there's only one planet, there's only one person, there's only one day, and there's only one room. And we created a construct where we're pretending there's many so we can experience our parts before going back to the whole.\"\n\nThe documents don't provide enough attribution detail to clearly say \"Person A said X\" and \"Person B said Y\" in a back-and-forth exchange. Could you clarify which specific passage you're referring to?","label":"Needs speaker turns separated recognizing the main speaker is speaking about the \"innerdance corpus\", and all the other speakers should be anonymous conversation partners"}
{"id":74,"question":"Write a one-sentence definition of InnerDance.","rag_answer":"Based on the documents, here is a one-sentence definition of InnerDance:\n\nInnerDance is a healing modality — not led by a healer, but one that creates the conditions where people heal themselves — experienced as \"being alone together,\" where participants go deeply inside themselves while doing it collectively as one.","label":"answer must write 'innerdance' lowercase and joined regardless of question spelling"}
{"id":75,"question":"Tell me about Inner Dance and how it works.","rag_answer":"Based on the documents, here is what is described about Inner Dance and how it works:\n\n## Origins and Context\n\nWhen innerdance came, there were a lot of things happening, mostly yoga and breathwork — and innerdance fell on top of that. It emerged from the convergence of breathwork, yoga, and psychedelics — bring those three things together, and you would end up with something like innerdance.\n\n## How It Differs from Yoga and Breathwork\n\nIn yoga, you activate the sympathetic nervous system, and then when you go into shavasana, you go into the parasympathetic nervous system. In breathwork, you activate the sympathetic still by breathing rapidly and then you let go. Innerdance inverts this process.\n\nIn innerdance, the movements are being determined by the moment — and the moment is not just the moment, but all of the past preempting the future. It's the space in between. So innerdance is, in a way, the new yoga — a yoga that is in the moment, not described, not coming from thousands of years ago, but the yoga of the 22nd century moment.\n\n## The Role of Music\n\nOne of the reasons innerdance works the way it does is that when you use music, you leave the sequential. Suddenly all the vibrations are overlapping with each other and people remember what is not one at a time, but all at once comes into memory.\n\nIn innerdance, in some moments, you are putting something to sleep, and then waking it up, then making it go to sleep again, and then waking it up again — creating a rhythmic wave dynamic.\n\n## The Brain and Body\n\nWhen innerdance triggers the motor cortex, the motor cortex facilitates change — a shift in movement — maybe because it opens up different dopamine pathways, serotonin pathways, and so on, causing the auditory, visual, and linguistic centers to change.\n\nThat's why innerdance is never prescribed, and why there is a diversity of movements in the innerdance process.\n\n## Its Transformative Potential\n\nWhat makes innerdance so salient and important is that everything you know actually began with how you experienced it in your body — particularly in how you moved your body.\n\nIt's the relationship between the self and the other through movement that creates this triangle — so when you learn to move in a different way, the whole structure of understanding changes.","label":"Actually the correct formatting is innerdance was used"}
{"id":76,"question":"Give me a short tagline for an Inner-Dance workshop.","rag_answer":"Based on the documents, here are a few taglines inspired by key concepts from the Inner Dance corpus:\n\n**\"Return to Your Body. Transform Your World.\"**\n\nThis is grounded in the idea that \"everything that you know actually began with how you experienced it in your body — particularly in how you moved your body.\"\n\nOr alternatively:\n\n**\"Move Differently. Become Different.\"**\n\nRooted in the principle that \"when you learn to move in a different way, this whole structure changes.\"","label":"output must use 'innerdance'"}
